State of Crypto Fundraising Q2 2024
Dylan Bane

9 hours ago   14 min read

Key Insights

  • Fundraising volume increased 22.5% QoQ, continuing an upward trend. However, June's fundraising volume decreased by 33.8% from May's, reflecting a possible slowdown in funding as markets cooled.
  • The most notable deals included Monad ($225 million), Farcaster ($150 million), Berachain ($100 million), Polymarket ($70 million), Babylon ($70 million)
  • Paradigm dominated fundraising among VCs, leading 3 of the top 5 early-stage deals this quarter.
  • The Networks Sector saw the most fundraising volume this quarter at $857 million, accounting for 23.7% of total fundraising volume.

Deal volume grew by 22.5% in Q2 to $3.65B, while deal count rose by 25.3% to $902 million QoQ. The Networks Sector raised the most of any sector, at $857 million, with the Financial Sector following closely in second at $773 million and the Infrastructure Sector in third at $687 million. Paradigm dominated funding among venture capitalists, leading 3 of the 5 largest early-stage deals this quarter.

The most notable Q2 deals covered in the Messari April and May fundraising reports include:

  • Monad: $225 million round led by Paradigm. Monad is building an optimistic parallel execution L1 with EVM compatibility.
  • Farcaster: $150 million Series A round led by Paradigm. Farcaster is a decentralized social media protocol that achieved significant traction in early 2024.
  • Berachain: $100 million Series B round led by Framework Ventures. Berachain is an L1 introducing a Proof-of-Liquidity (PoL) mechanism to address issues with Proof-of-Stake (PoS) designs.
  • Polymarket: $70 million Series A + B rounds led by General Catalyst and Founders Fund, respectively. Polymarket is a decentralized prediction market that grew in usage in Q2 from the 2024 U.S. election and political prediction markets.
  • Babylon: $70 million Series B round led by Paradigm. Babylon offers Bitcoin staking to secure Cosmos-Based Networks.

Note: Messari is in the process of adding additional public token sale data. Thus, historical data shown in this report may deviate from previous reports.

Networks Sector

This quarter's most funded sector was Networks, accounting for 23.7% of total fundraising volume. Fundraising volume rose significantly by 52.2%, accompanied by a 27.2% increase in deal count. The increase in volume was driven primarily by a few mega deals in the sector. Monad ($225 million), Berachain ($100 million), and Iotex ($50 million) took up 43% of the total amount raised among Networks in Q2. All three of these deals were covered previously in Messaris April and May fundraising reports.

Avail

In June, Avail raised a $43 million Series A round led by Founders Fund, Dragonfly Capital, and Cyber Fund. This round follows a $27 million Seed round raised less than four months prior in February. Avail is a Data Availability (DA) network that spun out of Polygon in 2023.

Avail is one of the newest entrants in the DA layer space, following Celestia and EigenDA. The question for Avail is how it can differentiate itself from its competitors to become the premier DA solution within the modular scaling stack. So far, Avail has advanced the narrative of building the Unification Layer for Web3, solving cross-chain and rollup interoperability issues.

The Unification Layer includes:

  • Avail DA: The base Data Availability layer.
  • Avail Nexus: Proof aggregation and sequencer selection ZK roll-up built on top of Avail DA.
  • Avail Fusion: Crypto-economic security layer secured by BTC, ETH, and other assets.

The bull case: Coming out of Polygon, Avail has the engineering talent, resources, and credibility to position itself as a premier DA solution. With Celestia launching in late 2023 and the modular ecosystem still in its infancy, Avail has time to win market share and build one of the strongest brands in the DA space. Furthermore, Avail is well-positioned to adapt to market needs and address specific niches as they emerge. Avail will be among the top DA layers in a multi-billion dollar rollup ecosystem if the modular thesis proves successful.

The bear case: Avail seeks to create an integrated solution with its Unification Layer for the increasingly complex modular landscape. In a way, this is going backward rather than forward. For blockchain developers wanting flexibility and customization, using Celestia for DA and other custom infrastructure already makes sense. For blockchain developers wanting simplicity, integrated L1s like Solana make sense. Its not clear why developers would choose Avail over other solutions.

For more insight into DA layers - check out Messaris The Modular Blockchain Landscape and Celestia: Does it Make Cents?

Conduit

Conduit raised a $37 million Series A round led by Paradigm and Haun Ventures. Conduit is a Rollup-as-a-Service (RaaS) provider that makes creating customizable rollups within the modular stack easy.

Conduit is one of the emerging major RaaS providers along with Caldera, Gelato, and others. The long-term success of RaaS providers depends on the growth of the modular ecosystem and increased demand for customized rollup solutions.

The bull case: Conduit has already surpassed significant milestones, with its rollups securing over $1.2 billion in TVL and processing 20% of Ethereum transactions. Additionally, large players in the crypto industry have worked and partnered with Conduit, including Aevo, friend.tech, Zora, Mode, and others. Conduits user-friendly deployment process seems to have found product-market fit. If the modular ecosystem continues to grow, Conduit will likely grow along with it.

The bear case: Conduits prospects rely on Ethereum's successful adoption of the modular thesis and validated developer interest in customized roll-up solutions. If growth in the Ethereum ecosystem stagnates, Conduit will find itself fighting for market share in a highly competitive market. Caldera, a RaaS-providing competitor, has also surpassed $1 billion in TVL, demonstrating the strength of competitors. How Conduit truly differentiates itself is unclear. All RaaS providers aim to provide customers with a user-friendly, low-friction, and dependable deployment process. Conduit will need to figure out how it can build a moat in a space where it has no clear structural advantages at present.

For more insight into RaaS providers and Conduit - check out Messaris The Rollups as a Service Ecosystem and Conduit Integrations - Enhancing OP Stack RaaS.

Financial Sector

Fundraising volume increased by 9.2% to $773 million, while deal count stayed flat, decreasing by 0.7% to 129 in Q2. With the highest number of deals among the top three sectors for fundraising volume, the Financial sector demonstrated a greater balance in funding across the sector, with no deals over $100 million this quarter. Notable Q2 financial deals covered in Messaris April and May fundraising reports include:

  • Polymarket: $70 million Series A + B rounds covered above.
  • Securitize: $47 million Strategic Funding round led by Blackrock. Securitize facilitates investments in private markets, funds, and alternative assets through tokenizing RWAs.
  • Ellipsis Labs: $20 million Seed round led by Paradigm. Ellipsis is the core developer of Phoenix, an on-chain central limit order book (CLOB) on Solana.
  • Agora: $12 million Seed round led by Dragonfly Capital. With institutional support from VanEck, Agora hopes to leverage relationships and integrations to provide a higher utility stablecoin.

M^0

M^0 raised a $35 million Series A round led by Bain Capital Crypto. M^0 enables institutions to mint crypto-dollar stablecoins backed by short-term U.S. treasuries as collateral.

M^0s vision is to create a collateral-backed stablecoin that is more decentralized than Circles USDC or Tethers USDT. It does this by allowing financial institutions to mint M tokens, which are backed by US treasuries and held in custody by a network of independent entities that interact both with the decentralized protocol and the existing legal system. This distributed custody allows for greater censorship resistance and decentralization as every participating entity would have to coordinate to deny the usage of M tokens.

The bull case: Stablecoins are one of the few killer apps in crypto, with the total stablecoin supply exceeding $150 billion at the end of 2023. A significant drawback of USDC and USDT is that they ultimately rely on their issuing companies, which are subject to regulations. These companies could be forced to void the value of their stablecoins, increasing the risk of holding these assets. By distributing the issuance and custody of M tokens among a diverse set of financial institutions, M stands to decrease the risk of censorship resistance compared to existing options. Even if Tether and USDC hold 71% and 21% of the stablecoin market, respectively, a small level of de-risking could lead to significant market capture of the massive stablecoin market for M^0.

The bear case: M^0s ultimate reliance on existing legal systems puts into question whether M tokens can gain sufficient trust to be considered more reliable to on-chain users than existing collateral backed stablecoins. Its unclear at this point whether on-chain users will perceive M^0 as de-risking the possession of collateralized stablecoins. Barring a legal or operational crisis for Circle and Tether, there may not be enough impetus for on-chain stablecoin holders to consider switching to M tokens.

Infrastructure Sector

Infrastructure fundraising volume grew by 22.4% to $687 million, while deal count fell by 70.1% to 26 in Q2. The increase in volume while deal count plummeted was driven by significant raises from mining infrastructure companies, including Hut 8 Mining ($150 million), Bitdeer ($100 million), and Auradine ($80 million). These three raises alone accounted for 48% of deal volume in the Infrastructure Sector. Notable Q2 infrastructure deals covered in Messaris April and May fundraising reports include Bitdeer, Auradine, and Babylon.

Nexus Laboratories

Nexus Laboratories raised a $25 million Series A round led by Pantera Capital and Lightspeed Venture Partners. Nexus is building a zero-knowledge Virtual Machine (zkVM) focused on scalable proofs for large-scale computation.

With rapid advances in zk technology over the last few years, much of blockchain infrastructure is adapting to incorporate zk much sooner than anticipated. Zk proofs promise to scale Ethereum faster and cheaper than fraud proofs, and zk rollups appear increasingly likely to replace optimistic rollups over the next five years. From identity proving to generative AI training, the quality of zk proving is becoming increasingly critical to scaling blockchain use cases.

Nexus hopes to accelerate the development of zk tech to unlock the full potential of trustless proving. Its ultimate vision is to build a zkVM supercomputer running at over a trillion CPU cycles per second that can instantly prove the worlds most important computations. The question for zk companies like Nexus is primarily technical. Can Nexus develop the most effective zk prover tech faster than their competitors and grow integrations with their zkVM quickly enough to build network effects?

The bull case: Nexus has a highly impressive team, including the inventor of pairing-based zkSNARKs, the former Chief Cryptographer at Jump who invented decentralized beacons, the President of the International Association for Cryptologic Research (IACR), and many more members at the top of cryptography. The advisors are equally impressive, consisting of cryptography professors and cryptographic researchers from institutions such as UT Austin and Google. Nexus is bringing premier cryptographers, mathematicians, and engineers together to develop the zk prover for the internet. Given the highly technical nature of zk development, the strength of the Nexus team bodes well for its potential to deliver the most scalable zk prover to the market.

The bear case: zk tech is highly complex, and the pace of innovation could stall. Nexus might not realize its vision, and the scalability of zk proofs might not prove effective enough to become a viable solution for the industry. Furthermore, some of the most intelligent teams in crypto are working on zkVMs, including Polygon, RISC-Zero, ZK-Sync, and others. These teams have a multiple-year head start over Nexus in building their brand and reputation, which may prove challenging to overcome.

For more insight on zk proof markets, check out our Deep Dive into Proof Marketplaces Report.

Ora

Ora raised a $20 million Series A round from investors, including Polychain Capital and Hashkey Capital. Ora tokenizes AI models and enables decentralized AI oracles.

The generative AI boom has led to a proliferation in activity in Crypto x AI, with the industry exploring potential use cases at the intersection of both technologies. Ora is building infrastructure for future interactions between crypto and AI. Its core value proposition is enabling smart contracts to interact with AI natively, using its oracle built with proprietary Optimistic Machine Learning (opML) technology. As with most blockchain infrastructure projects, Ora's success hinges on the long-term growth of the use cases that leverage the infrastructure it provides.

The bull case: The potential of blockchain to counter the centralized control of AI by Big Tech conglomerates is likely to attract significant capital in the coming years. As the first dedicated AI oracle, Ora is well-positioned to be one of the foremost infrastructure providers for decentralized AI interactions. Additionally, Ora is attempting to tokenize AI models through Initial Model Offerings (IMOs). This could distribute profits from generative AI to token holders, helping fulfill the promise of decentralizing the AI industry and driving more demand for Oras decentralized AI oracle at the same time. If AI dApps and demand for on-chain AI grow, Ora stands to benefit significantly.

The bear case: The viability of Crypto x AI use cases is uncertain, with few use cases appearing scalable at this point. Centralized companies have structural advantages in providing low-cost and scalable solutions, making it difficult for on-chain use cases to compete without significant progress in zk-proving technology. Ora may not have enough customers to reach breakout success in this scenario. Furthermore, large blockchain infrastructure providers will likely enter Oras target markets if AI use cases demonstrate success. Chainlink has already explored potential AI integrations with its CCIP and oracle services, showing the close attention established players are paying to this space.

Symbiotic

Symbiotic raised a $5.8 million Seed round led by Paradigm and Cyber Fund. Symbiotic is a re-staking protocol for the Ethereum ecosystem.

The protocol announced a surprise seed round on June 11th, reaching $250 million in TVL within 24 hours of launch and crossing the $1 billion mark in early July.

The success of Eigenlayer ($15 billion TVL) has led to new restaking platforms entering the market, including Karak in April and Symbiotic in June. Just as hundreds of L2s emerged hoping to scale Ethereum, a similar phenomenon may occur with restaking protocols. The long-term question for Symbiotic is whether it can effectively compete with Eigenlayer and other new participants for market share in the restaking market.

The bull case: Symbiotics immense TVL growth within one month of launch already seems to show product market fit. Additionally, Symbiotic has partnered with high-profile protocols, including Ethena, further demonstrating high levels of demand for Symbiotic restaking pools and integrations. The protocol offers support for any ERC-20 token, along with support for non-Ethereum native tokens. This contrasts with Eigenlayer, which only offers support for ETH and liquid-staked derivatives of ETH. Support for a broader set of restaked tokens could position Symbiotic as the premier staking platform for all of crypto. As one of the first movers in the restaking market, Symbiotic is poised to grow with increased demand for shared security as the crypto industry grows.

The bear case: Symbiotic could face intense competition from other restaking platforms, competing to offer the most attractive yields. The platform could also struggle to provide a differentiated product in the long run, if restaking becomes commoditized. Additionally, restaking and AVSs are novel concepts that need more time to be fully validated. In particular, restaking yields may not prove attractive enough for restakers to incur added slashing risk. Overall, its too early to predict how the restaking space will evolve.

For more insight into restaking, shared security, and Eigenlayer - check out Messaris

  • Eigenlayer: From I Cant to EIGEN.
  • The Eigenlayer Question.
  • Babylon: Bitcoin Shared Security and Staking.

Concluding Thoughts

Q2 saw continued fundraising volume and deal count growth, growing 22.5% and 25.3%, respectively. However, deal volume plummeted by 33.8% in June compared to May, showing signs of a cooldown. With a 39.5% YoY decrease in fundraising volume from June 2023 to June 2024, investment interest in crypto seems to be declining. This could be attributed to a reversal of the early 2024 crypto bull market, shifting investor interest to a hot AI market, or an oversaturation of VC investment into blockchain infrastructure. Paradigm led the way as the most prominent early-stage investor in the space, leading 3 of the 5 largest early-stage rounds this quarter. Q3 will reveal whether crypto fundraising volume will continue to grow or if a decrease in fundraising could coincide with a possible bear market.
